english:
  title: A Response Enclosed with a Letter to Dongjin
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: The Mongols, as they are called, are consumed by suspicion and cruelty beyond measure. Though we might seek peace with them, such agreements prove insufficient to earn their trust. Our nation's friendship with them does not spring from genuine desire, yet as I reported in my previous letter, in the year of Gimyo, when pressed by circumstances at Gangdong Fortress, we were compelled to make a covenant of peace. And so when their armies came before, though they had sworn their oaths, they abandoned their word and unleashed such savagery that our nation chose to bear the blame ourselves rather than follow their example. Thus we received them as we always had, treating them with courtesy and honor. Now, though our nation has relocated its capital, we receive their armies with even greater warmth. Yet they show no gratitude for such kindness. Instead, they roam the near borders at will, committing cruelty and plunder more terrible than ever before. Because of this, all the provinces and districts have withdrawn behind their walls, holding firm, some fortifying themselves behind rivers, watching and waiting for what comes next. Yet the Mongols grow ever more ambitious in their appetite for conquest and attack. How can the local commanders be bound by the directives of the capital or by those who counsel reconciliation? Must they not protect themselves from the fate of those who feed the tiger only to be devoured by it? Thus our forces do more than defend—driven by the suffering of the people, they venture forth to meet the enemy in battle, killing and capturing many officials and soldiers. As recently as the sixteenth day of the twelfth month this year, at Cheonin, a small fortress under Susju, our forces engaged them in battle. We shot and killed their commander Satari. Many were taken captive. The remaining forces scattered in disarray. From that moment, their spirits broken and unable to find rest, they have apparently turned their armies to retreat. Yet they did not gather as one to depart—some have gone ahead, others lag behind, uncertain whether to march east or north. Thus the date of their departure cannot be fixed, nor can we know their destination with certainty. I respectfully urge Your Majesty to issue secret orders for reconnaissance of their movements.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gimyo year (己卯) refers to 1219 in the Gregorian calendar, during the Goryeo period when pressure from the Mongols intensified.
  - key: ''
    value: Gangdong Fortress (江東城) was a strategic military stronghold during this period of conflict.
  - key: ''
    value: Satari (沙打里) was a Mongol military leader whose death is recorded as a significant victory for Goryeo forces.
  - key: ''
    value: Susju (水州) and Cheonin (處仁) were administrative regions in medieval Korea.
